http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org


[1]
Date: Thu 7 Jul 2011
Source: CBC (Canadian Broadcasting Corporation) News [edited]
http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2011/07/07/outbreak-difficile-fedhelp.html


Another death has been tied to an outbreak of the _Clostridium
difficile_ superbug in Ontario's Niagara region, hospital officials
say. A 3rd patient related to the _C. difficile_ outbreak at a
Welland, Ontario, hospital died Wednesday afternoon [6 Jul 2011], the
Niagara Health System said Thursday [7 Jul 2011]. At least 17 people
-- mainly elderly -- have died in the Niagara region since the
outbreak was declared 28 May 2011.

Sue Matthews, president and CEO of the Niagara Health System [NHS],
told reporters that the Ontario Ministry of Health offered a field
epidemiologist to help learn more about the outbreak. The
epidemiologist arrived in the region on Thursday afternoon, Matthews
said. Epidemiologists collect and analyze data to monitor trends in
the outbreak, she said. A field epidemiologist is helping [to
investigate] the outbreak, says Niagara Health System president and
CEO Sue Matthews. CBC

Robert Cyrenne, a spokesperson for the Public Health Agency of Canada
[PHAC], said the agency sent a field epidemiologist in response to a
request from the Ontario government, acting on behalf of the Niagara
Region Public Health. "Upon request, PHAC regularly assists provinces
and territories by providing field epidemiologists," Cyrenne said. The
field epidemiologist is a federally-funded employee based in Toronto
and deployed as an additional resource for the outbreak, said Andrew
Morrison, a spokesperson for the Ontario Ministry of Health. The
federal agency can also collaborate with provincial and
infection-control experts to help prevent, diagnose and analyze
strains.

The Niagara region deaths include 10 at St Catharines General, 4 at
the Greater Niagara General, and 3 at the Welland Site. Outbreaks were
declared 23 Jun 2011 at the Greater Niagara General and Welland
sites.

On Wednesday [6 Jul 2011], a 4th health facility in the Niagara region
confirmed an outbreak. The Hotel Dieu Shaver Health and Rehabilitation
Centre said 4 of its patients tested positive within the past few
weeks, prompting officials to investigate further and declare the
outbreak. The other 2 patients are not part of the outbreak, said the
centre, which is not part of the Niagara Health System.

The federal government's help came as Ontario's associate chief
medical officer of health, Dr David Williams, said there were now 10
declared outbreaks in hospitals and one suspected. The hospitals are
in Guelph, St. Catharines, Niagara Falls, Napanee, Toronto, Welland,
Orangeville, Hamilton and Mississauga, the Canadian Press reported. An
outbreak, Williams said, could be as few as 2 cases in a ward, and
there are regularly 4 to 6 outbreaks happening in the province's
hospitals.

_C. difficile_ causes diarrhea and is one of the most common
infections in hospitals and long-term care facilities. Most cases of
_C. difficile_ hit people taking antibiotics. In severe cases, it can
cause critical illness and death in elderly or very sick patients.
People most at risk after exposure are typically of advanced age, and
with underlying illnesses such as inflammatory bowel disease or
immunodeficiency, who are also taking antibiotics.

