Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[_Clostridium difficile_-associated disease (CDAD) is a spectrum of
potentially fatal illnesses that includes diarrhea, pseudomembranous
colitis, and toxic megacolon. _C. difficile_ is the most common cause
of bacterial diarrhea and pseudomembranous colitis in hospitalized
patients, and antimicrobial drug therapy is the most important risk
factor associated with the acquisition of _C. difficile_.

The Niagara Health System (NHS) is located in the Niagara region of
southern Ontario, Canada, between Lake Ontario and Lake Erie, and is
Ontario's largest multi-site hospital system. NHS is comprised of 7
sites across the 12 municipalities that make up the Regional
Municipality of Niagara, namely the Douglas Memorial Site in Fort
Erie; Greater Niagara General; Site in Niagara Falls;
Niagara-on-the-Lake Site; Ontario Street Site in St. Catharine's; Port
Colborne Site; St Catharine's General Site; and Welland Site
(http://www.niagarahealth.on.ca/services/). However, the exact
number of NHS facilities involved in the CDAD outbreak is not stated
in the most current (2nd) news release above, but the 1st news release
says that the outbreak was not restricted just to the NHS group of
healthcare facilities and that 10 hospitals were involved at that
time. This is not surprising, since patients discharged from one
institution after a bout of CDAD may be subsequently admitted to
another institution in the region with a relapse of the infection.
Relapse rates for CDAD can be as high as 25 percent.

The news releases also do not state whether there is one or more
genotypes involved in the regional outbreak and if the hypervirulent
strain ribotype 027 is involved. Although we are not given the total
number of patients infected, 35 deaths suggest there may be a high
case-fatality rate. That and the occurrence of community-acquired
cases suggest that ribotype 027 may be present.

Recent outbreaks of CDAD with increased severity, high relapse rate,
and significant mortality, have been related to the emergence of a
new, hypervirulent _C. difficile_ strain in North America, Japan, and
Europe. The emerging strain, which hyper-produces toxins A and B, is
referred to as North American pulsed-field type 1 and polymerase chain
reaction (PCR) ribotype 027. This epidemic strain is
characteristically resistant to fluoroquinolones, the use of which is
one risk factor for disease due to this ribotype (Drudy D, Kyne L,
O'Mahony R, Fanning S: gyrA mutations in fluoroquinolone-resistant
_Clostridium difficile_ PCR-027. Emerg Infect Dis 2007; 13(3):504-5.
Available at http://www.cdc.gov/EID/content/13/3/504.htm). This
strain is also referred to as the "Quebec strain" (see
http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dhqp/pdf/infDis/Cdiff_ICHE08_05.pdf).

Preventing the spread of _C. difficile_ in healthcare facilities
involves clinical and microbiologic surveillance of hospitalized
patients with diarrhea for _C. difficile_ and heightened infection
control measures, including prompt isolation of patients with _C.
difficile_-positive diarrhea, or cohorting where isolation rooms are
not available, combined with particular emphasis on hand hygiene and
control of the inappropriate use of antimicrobial agents
(http://www.shea-online.org/Assets/files/position_papers/Cldiff95.PDF).

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Canada is available at
http://healthmap.org/r/15ST and St. Catharine's and Welland can be
found on a map of Ontario at
http://listingsca.com/common/maps/ca/onmapg.gif. - Mod.ML]
